AGI - Ukraine is ready to come to peace after three years from the Russian invasion. <b> Gedda</b>, Saudi Arabia, talks between the Ukrainian and US delegation, the first after the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-03-01/scontro-trump-zelensky-nato-fuori-dallo-studio-ovale-30239482/" Kiev announced it.
The Ukrainian delegation is led by the Head of Cabinet of the Presidency, <b>Andriy Yermak</b>, and includes the President's Adviser <b>Pavlo Palisa</b>, Foreign Minister <b>Andrii Sybiha</b> and Minister of Defense <b> Rustem Umerov</b>. For the United States there are the Secretary of State <b>Marc Rubio</b> and the National Security Council <b>Mike Waltz</b>.
<h2>Yemark: "Never peace has been closer"</h2>
"While I arrive at Gedda, the ceasefire in the war that the Russian Federation unleashed against my country, which lasted three years, never seemed closer to me," wrote <b> Andriy Yermak</b> in an intervention on the Guardian >. He stressed that a ceasefire > requires crucial conditions to ensure lasting peace > including political and financial pressure on Russia and a stronger and resilient Europe.
"Ensure a significant ceasefire is the first step. Europe must be ready to act to ensure its security > and Russia must understand the political and economic cost of using force," added Yermak.
<h2>The Moscow braking
According to the Kremlin, Ukraine could have made a massive night attack on Moscow to block peace negotiations. The spokesman <b>Dmitri Peskov</b> said that the action "would jeopardize the tendency to the newly emerged dialogue".
<h2> Commitment for peace
Entering the talks, Yermak reiterated: "We are ready to do anything to reach peace." Ukraine wants to end the war and build a more secure and resilient Europe. >
